Grip Project Report

25 May 2016

Maximum grip aperture (on reach to grasp)

The maximum grip aperture is the maximum distance between the markers on the thumb and index finger during the period between when the hand left the table and when it touched the stick (this period is labeled as grip in our annotation system).

We fit a hierarchical (mixed effects) linear regression model.

The outcome (dependent) variable is:

  • the maximum grip aperture (in mm)

The predictor (independent) variables are:

  • the size of the stick in centimeters (centered at 8 cm, where 1 unit difference is 1 cm difference in stick size)
  • the configuration of the fins (closed, none, open; where closed is the reference level)
  • the interaction between the size of the stick and configuration of fins

There are varying intercepts by subject, and the effects of all the predictors (including interactions) are also allowed to vary by subject (these are the mixed effects). The full formula1 for this model is:

maxGrip ~ stickcmCentered * fins + (1 + stickcmCentered * fins | obsisSubj)

Coefficient plot

These are the estimates of the effect sizes for the predictors (and interactions) in the model. The dot is the point estimate, the thick line is the 95% confidence interval, and the thin line the 99% confidence interval. One rule of thumb is: if the confidence intervals do not the effect is statistically significant.

Model predictions

These are predictions from the model for specific conditions. The dots are point estimates, and the lines are 95% confidence intervals.

Size estimation

The mean grip aperture is the mean of the distance measurements between the markers on the thumb and index finger during the period when the subject said the word ready (this period is labeled as steady in our annotation system).

We fit a hierarchical (mixed effects) linear regression model.

The outcome (dependent) variable is:

  • the mean grip aperture (in mm)

The predictor (independent) variables are:

  • the size of the stick in centimeters (centered at 8 cm, where 1 unit difference is 1 cm difference in stick size)
  • the configuration of the fins (closed, none, open; where closed is the reference level)
  • the interaction between the size of the stick and configuration of fins

There are varying intercepts by subject, and the effects of all the predictors are also allowed to vary by subject (these are the mixed effects). The full formula2 for this model is:

meanGrip ~ stickcmCentered * fins + (1 + stickcmCentered + fins | obsisSubj)

Coefficient plot

These are the estimates of the effect sizes for the predictors (and interactions) in the model. The dot is the point estimate, the thick line is the 95% confidence interval, and the thin line the 99% confidence interval. One rule of thumb is: if the confidence intervals do not the effect is statistically significant.

These are predictions from the model for specific conditions. The dots are point estimates, and the lines are 95% confidence intervals.

Maximum grip aperture during gesture

The maximum grip aperture is the maximum distance between the markers on the thumb and index finger during the period between when the hand left the table and when it looked like it was picking up the stick during gesture.

We fit a hierarchical (mixed effects) linear regression model.

The outcome (dependent) variable is:

  • the maximum grip aperture (in mm)

The predictor (independent) variables are:

  • the size of the stick in centimeters as a categorical variable (factor), with seven as the reference level.
  • the configuration of the fins (closed, none, open; where closed is the reference level)
  • the interaction between the size of the stick (as a categorical variable) and configuration of fins

There are varying intercepts by subject, and the effects of all the predictors (including interactions) are also allowed to vary by subject (these are the mixed effects). The full formula3 for this model is:

maxGrip ~ stick * fins + (1 + stick * fins | obsisSubj)

Coefficient plot

These are the estimates of the effect sizes for the predictors (and interactions) in the model. The dot is the point estimate, the thick line is the 95% confidence interval, and the thin line the 99% confidence interval. One rule of thumb is: if the confidence intervals do not the effect is statistically significant.

These are predictions from the model for specific conditions. The dots are point estimates, and the lines are 95% confidence intervals.

Mean grip aperture during gesture (movement)

The mean and median distance between the markers on the thumb and index finger during the period between when the hand was moving during gesture.

We fit a hierarchical (mixed effects) linear regression model.

The outcome (dependent) variable is:

  • the mean grip aperture (in mm)

The predictor (independent) variables are:

  • the size of the stick in centimeters as a categorical variable (factor), with seven as the reference level.
  • the configuration of the fins (closed, none, open; where closed is the reference level)
  • the interaction between the size of the stick (as a categorical variable) and configuration of fins

There are varying intercepts by subject, and the effects of all the predictors are also allowed to vary by subject (these are the mixed effects). The full formula4 for this model is:

meanGrip ~ stick * fins + (1 + stick + fins | obsisSubj)

Coefficient plot

These are the estimates of the effect sizes for the predictors (and interactions) in the model. The dot is the point estimate, the thick line is the 95% confidence interval, and the thin line the 99% confidence interval. One rule of thumb is: if the confidence intervals do not the effect is statistically significant.

These are predictions from the model for specific conditions. The dots are point estimates, and the lines are 95% confidence intervals.
